<font color="#FF0000">TO DOC DEL</font><br>
<tt>Mon Jan 19 10:32:51 US/Eastern 1998
</tt><p>
My Dear Brother Doc Del<br><br>
Thank you for sharing,<br><br>
We do make light of some serious conservations at times, but when I receive them from You, Ed, Gary, Art, Bob and others I receive them with great honor. Because that's what kept us sane in Nam, and that's also how we expressed how much we cared about each other. I don't think it was just a Marine Corps thing.<br><br>
My Captain has fought cancer for years, often he says when he gets real sick, he thinks of his men in India Company, and when he really can't stand the pain, he wraps us around himself and that brings him comfort. It's all just another rice paddy we have to cross doc, and we'll be there to help each other cross it.<br><br>
I understand what you wrote, about having to:<br><br>
&quot;sit and re-read posts from others for a couple of days just so I can understand what they want me to understand.&quot; <br><br>
I do that mostly because half the time I can't find my glasses to read and the other half because I've forgotten where I put them.<br><br>
ED, understands the:<br>
&quot;stereotypical basket case, slouch in a chair, drooling in his own lap, making babbeling noises.&quot; But mostly he isn't babbeling, he’s just passing gas. <br><br>
I've been told that one day after he hit the old fart sack, he farted so loud that it woke up the dog and his wife kicked him out of bed. That is also why, when I e-mail Ed, I, T y p e,  r e a l,  S l o w, so he'll understand what  I ' m  s a y i n g.<br><br>
But I wouldn’t trade Ed for an M60, and Doc, when you’re not feeling good, just wrap us and those you helped in Nam around yourself. If you ever need someone to help carry you across an open rice paddy field just call, I’ve done that before.<br><br>
In your service and His<br><br>
Cook Barela<br>

